<dl id="n03020c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n03" href="#n03020c">N03 (VI.B.3)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n03all.htm#n03020c"> 20(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> 2 hilltops ~ <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n03020c"><li>FW 22.03 </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/lexa.htm#n03020c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/l39a.htm#n03020c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n03020c">MS BL 47472-26</ms> </li><li>JJA 44:129 <a name="ad2" href="../../ff/fdra/ada.htm#ad2">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/a/ad2.htm#n03020c">Draft: I.1&sect;2.2</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The writer of <font color="green">[an ancient Irish]</font> manuscript says that &ldquo;the First Order <font color="green">[of Irish saints]</font> was most holy, the Second Order holier, and the Third holy. The First glowed like the sun in the fervour of their charity; the Second cast a pale radiance like the moon; the Third shone like the aurora. These Three Orders the blessed Patrick foreknew, enlightened by heavenly wisdom, when in prophetic vision he saw at first all Ireland ablaze, and <mark>afterwards only the mountains on fire;</mark> and at last saw lamps lit in the valleys.&rdquo; <small> J.M. Flood, <a name="JMFI" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JMFI"><cite title="source">Ireland: Its Saints and Scholars</cite></a> (n.d) 43-4</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
